In the previous section, I selected the GBM model, as it had the smallest MAE. Now, I will map and plot its predictions to compare them with the actual sale prices. First, I merge the manhattan_final dataframe with the manhattan_ints dataframe that contains the latitude and longitudesI call the latter lat_lons.

Merge manhattan_final with manhattan_int to get lat, lons

manhattan_final <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lcao21/GIS3_Final_Project/master/Data/manhattan_final.csv")


lat_lons <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lcao21/GIS3_Final_Project/master/Data/manhattan_ints.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Keep relevant columns
lat_lons <- lat_lons[c("ADDRESS", "lat", "lon", "SALE.PRICE", "num_schools", "num_food", "num_parks", "num_subway", "RESIDENTIAL.UNITS", "LAND.SQUARE.FEET", "neighborhood_ord")]

# Convert LAND.SQUARE.FEET to integer to match manhattan_final
lat_lons$LAND.SQUARE.FEET <- gsub(",","",lat_lons$LAND.SQUARE.FEET)
lat_lons[c("LAND.SQUARE.FEET")] <- data.frame(apply(lat_lons[c("LAND.SQUARE.FEET")], 2, as.integer))

Left join manhattan_final to lat_lons

manhattan_ll <- merge(manhattan_final, lat_lons)

Load fit_gbm model

set.seed(600)
in_training <- createDataPartition(manhattan_ll$SALE.PRICE, p = 0.70, list=FALSE)
training <- droplevels(manhattan_ll[in_training,])
training <- training[c(1:8)]

fit_gbm <- gbm(SALE.PRICE ~ ., data = training ,distribution = "gaussian", n.trees = 10000, shrinkage = 0.01, interaction.depth = 4)

Predict manhattan sale prices from (scaled) manhattan_ll

y_hat_gbm <- predict(fit_gbm, manhattan_ll[c(1:8)], n.trees = 10000)
manhattan_ll["gbm_predicted"] <- y_hat_gbm
manhattan_ll <- manhattan_ll %>%
  select("gbm_predicted", everything())
head(formattable(manhattan_ll))

Get map borders

height <- max(manhattan_ll$lat) - min(manhattan_ll$lat)
width <- max(manhattan_ll$lon) - min(manhattan_ll$lon)
borders <- c(bottom  = min(manhattan_ll$lat)  - 0.2 * height,
             top     = max(manhattan_ll$lat)  + 0.2 * height,
             left    = min(manhattan_ll$lon) - 0.2 * width,
             right   = max(manhattan_ll$lon) + 0.2 * width)
borders
##    bottom       top      left     right 
##  40.67401  40.91134 -74.03133 -73.88918

Map actual (scaled) sale prices

map <- get_stamenmap(borders, zoom = 11, maptype = "terrain")

actual_map <- ggmap(map) +
  geom_point(data = manhattan_ll, mapping = aes(x = lon, y = lat, col = SALE.PRICE)) +
  scale_color_gradient("Scaled Sale Price",
                       low = "orange",
                       high = "purple",
                       labels = scales::dollar_format(prefix = "$")) + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Manhattan Home Prices")

A closer look: Upper Manhattan

Since I scaled neighborhood_ord, the original values do not hold. Nevertheless, there are still 15 unique values and once I sort them, I can use my original scaling from part 1 (data cleaning) to determine which scaled value is associated with which neighborhood

ord_values <- sort(unique(manhattan_ll$neighborhood_ord))

Filter for upper manhattan homes

upper_m <- manhattan_ll[manhattan_ll$neighborhood_ord %in% ord_values[c(1, 3:6, 8, 15)],]
upper_m$SALE.PRICE <- as.character(round(upper_m$SALE.PRICE, 4))
upper_m$gbm_predicted <- as.character(round(upper_m$gbm_predicted, 4))

upper_m_popups <- paste0("Actual $", upper_m$SALE.PRICE, " vs. Predicted $", upper_m$gbm_predicted)

Map neighborhoods by average difference in actual vs.predicted

Create a column of absolute differences

manhattan_ll$diff <- abs(manhattan_ll$gbm_predicted - manhattan_ll$SALE.PRICE)
manhattan_ll <- manhattan_ll %>%
  select("diff", everything())

Find mean absolute difference/error for each neighborhood

maes <- aggregate(manhattan_ll[, 1], list(manhattan_ll$neighborhood_ord), mean)
names(maes)[names(maes)=="Group.1"] <- "neighborhood_ord"
names(maes)[names(maes)=="x"] <- "MAE"

Merge with manhattan_ll

manhattan_maes <- merge(manhattan_ll, maes, all.x = TRUE)
manhattan_maes  <- manhattan_maes  %>%
  select("MAE", everything())

Map of homes by differences

ggmap(map) +
  geom_point(data = manhattan_maes, mapping = aes(x = lon, y = lat, col = diff)) +
  scale_color_gradient("|Predicted-Actual|",
                       low = "cadetblue4",
                       high = "cadetblue1",

Since Im calculating the intersection between neighborhoods and homes, I have to also prep the manhattan_maes dataframe, of which I made a copy of to use. By calculating the intersections, Im adhering to the neighborhood classifications from the shapefile, not the original 15 that I created since part 1. These new classifications, however, should not be that different or different at all.

Calculate intersection

maes_copy <- manhattan_maes
coordinates(maes_copy) <- c("lon", "lat")
proj4string(maes_copy) <- CRS("+init=epsg:4326")
maes_sf <- st_as_sf(maes_copy) %>% st_transform(4326)
inter <- as.data.frame(st_intersection(x = m_neighs, y = maes_sf))

Map it!

inter_poly <- as(st_as_sf(inter_poly), "Spatial")

tmap_mode("view")
tm_basemap("Stamen.TonerLite") + 
  tm_shape(inter_poly) +
  tm_polygons("MAE", palette = "viridis") +
  tm_tiles("Stamen.TonerLabels")
## Warning in `$.crs`(gm$shape.master_crs, "proj4string"): CRS uses proj4string,
## which is deprecated.

Neighborhood breakdown

tmap_mode("plot")
tm_shape(inter_poly) +
  tm_polygons("MAE", palette = "viridis") +
  tm_facets(by = "ntaname")

So the GBM seems to have best predicted home sale prices in 13 out of the 28 neighborhoods, including East Village and Harlem.
